  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 6:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 5:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " f.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀφορίσωσιν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] from the congregation of the synagogue and the intercourse of common life. This is the excommunication ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "נִדּוּי",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Buxtorf, Lex. Talm. s.v.). Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 9:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But that at that time there were already beside this simple excommunication one (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "חֵרֶם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") or two (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "חרם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "שַׁלַּתָא",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") still higher degrees (see, in general, Grotius on this passage; Winer, Realw.) is improbable (Gildemeister, Blendwerke d. vulgär. Ration. p. 10 ff.), and, moreover, is not to be inferred from what follows, wherein is depicted the hostility which is associated with the excommunication.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καὶ ἐκβάλωσι τ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὄν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὑμ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὡς πονηρ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐκβάλλειν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is just the German wegwerfen, in the sense of contemptuous rejection, Plato, Pol. ii. p. 377 C, Crit. p. 46 B; Soph. O. C. 637, 642; Ael. H. A. xi. 10; Kypke, I. p. 236; but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τὸ ὄνομα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is not auctoritas (Kypke), nor a designation of the character or the faith (de Wette), nor the name of Christian (Ewald), which idea (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 10:42",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 9:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") occurs in this place for the first time by means of the following ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἕνεκα τοῦ υἱοῦ τ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀνθρ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".; but the actual personal name, which designates the individual in question. Hence: when they shall have rejected your name (e.g. John, Peter, etc.) as evil, i.e. as being of evil meaning, because it represents an evil man in your person,—on account of the Son of man,—ye know yourselves as His disciples. The singular ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὄνομα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is distributive. Comp. Ael. H. A. 5. 4; Polyb. xviii. 28. 4; Krüger, § 44. 1. 7; Winer, p. 157 [E. T. 218], Others interpret wrongly: When they shall have exiled you (Kuinoel), to express which would have required ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὑμᾶς ὡς πονηρούς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; or: when they shall have struck out your names from the register of names (Beza and others quoted by Wolf, Michaelis also), which even in form would amount to an unusual tautology with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀφορίσ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".; or: when they shall have spread your name abroad as evil (defamed you) (Grotius, Bengel, Rosenmüller, Schegg), which is ungrammatical, and not to be established by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 22:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; or: when they declare it as evil (Bleek), which, nevertheless, would be very different from the classical ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἔπη ἐκβάλλειν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to cast up words, verba proferre (Hom. Il. vi. 324; Pind. Pyth. ii. 148); and, withal, how feeble and inexpressive!",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 6:22-23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In the corresponding passage in Mt. there is first an objective didactic statement about the persecuted. then an expansion in the second person. Here all is in the second person, and the terms employed are such as suited the experience of the early Christians, especially those belonging to the Jewish Church, suffering, at the hands of their unbelieving countrymen, wrong in the various forms indicated—hatred, separation, calumny, ejection.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀφορίσωσιν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " may point either to separation in daily life (Keil, Hahn) or to excommunication from the synagogue (so most commentaries) = the Talmudic ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "נִדָּה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In the former case one naturally finds the culminating evil of excommunication in the last clause—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐκβάλωσιν τὸ ὄ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὑ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". = erasing the name from the membership of the synagogue. In the latter case this clause will rather point to the vile calumnies afterwards heaped upon the excommunicated. “Absentium nomen, ut improborum hominum, differre rumoribus,” Grotius.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "hate you...separate you...reproach...cast out your name as evil",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] We have here four steps of persecution increasing in virulence:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(1) General hatred, (2) Exclusion from the synagogue, a lesser excommunication, viz. the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Neziphah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or exclusion for 30 days, or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Niddoui ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for 90 days (Gfrorer, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jahrh. d. Heils",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 1. 183; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 9:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Hence ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "aphorismos",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " means ‘",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "excommunication",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "’), (3) Violent slander, (4) The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Cherem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Shammata",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or greater excommunication,—permanent expulsion from the Synagogue and Temple (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 16:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The Jews pretended that our Lord was thus excommunicated to the blast of 400 ram’s horns by Joshua Ben Perachiah (Wagenseil, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Sota",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 1057), and was only crucified forty days after because no witness came forward in His favour.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
