  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 22.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Blessed are ye, when men shall hate you, and when they shall separate you from their company,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and shall reproach",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " you, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and cast out your name as evil, for the Son",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "man's sake.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " An onlook into the yet distant future. These words would be repeated by many a brave confessor in the days when persecution, at the hands of a far stronger and more far-reaching government than that of Jerusalem, should be the general lot of his followers. We find from pagan ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "writers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the next age that Christians were charged with plotting every vile and detestable crime that could be conceived against man-. kind (see, for instance, the historian Tacitus,  'Annal.,' 15:44; Suetonius, 'Nero.,' 16). Luke 6:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 5:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Son of Man",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The phrase is employed in the Old Testament as a circumlocution for man, with special reference to his frailty as contrasted with God (Numbers 23:19; Psalm 8:4; Job 25:6; Job 35:8; and eighty-nine times in Ezekiel). It had also a Messianic meaning (Daniel 7:13 sq.), to which our Lord referred in Matthew 24:30; Matthew 26:64. It was the title which Christ most frequently applied to himself; and there are but two instances in which it is applied to him by another, viz., by Stephen (Acts 7:56) and by John (Revelation 1:13; Revelation 14:14 :); and when acquiescing in the title \"Son of God,\" addressed to himself, he sometimes immediately after substitutes \"Son of Man\" (John 1:50, John 1:51; Matthew 26:63, Matthew 26:64).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The phrase is employed in the Old Testament as a circumlocution for man, with special reference to his frailty as contrasted with God (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Numbers 23:19",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 8:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Job 25:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Job 35:8",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; and eighty-nine times in Ezekiel). It had also a Messianic meaning (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Daniel 7:13",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " sq.), to which our Lord referred in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
